04188nam a22005655i 9780822387084DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223870847 a10.1515/97808223870842doi  a(DE-B1597)552599  a(OCoLC)1171574595  a(OCoLC)1110249033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM1271b.C656 2005 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a323.1/012221 aConnolly, William E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPluralism /cWilliam E. Connolly. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (206 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrelude -- tChapter 1 PLURALISM AND EVIL -- tChapter 2 PLURALISM AND RELATIVISM -- tChapter 3 PLURALISM AND THE UNIVERSE -- tInterlude -- tChapter 4 PLURALISM AND TIME -- tChapter 5 PLURALISM AND SOVEREIGNTY -- tPostlude: Belonging to Time -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past two decades, the renowned political theorist William E. Connolly has developed a powerful theory of pluralism as the basis of a territorial politics. In this concise volume, Connolly launches a new defense of pluralism, contending that it has a renewed relevance in light of pressing global and national concerns, including the war in Iraq, the movement for a Palestinian state, and the fight for gay and lesbian rights. Connolly contends that deep, multidimensional pluralism is the best way to promote justice and inclusion without violence. He advocates a deep pluralism-in contrast to shallow, secular pluralism-that helps to create space for different groups to bring their religious faiths into the public realm. This form of deep pluralism extends far beyond faith, encompassing multiple dimensions of social and personal lives, including household organization and sexuality.Connolly looks at pluralism not only in light of faith but also in relation to evil, ethics, relativism, globalization, and sovereignty. In the process, he engages many writers and theorists-among them, Spinoza, William James, Henri Bergson, Marcel Proust, Gilles Deleuze, Giorgio Agamben, Talal Asad, Michael Hardt, and Antonio Negri. Pluralism is the first book in which Connolly explains the relationship between pluralism and the experience of time, and he offers readings of several films that address how time is understood, including Time Code, Far from Heaven, Waking Life, and The Maltese Falcon. In this necessary book Connolly brings a compelling, accessible philosophical critique together with his personal commitment to an inclusive political agenda to suggest how we might-and why we must-cultivate pluralism within both society and ourselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCultural pluralismxPolitical aspects. 0aCultural pluralismzUnited States. 0aToleration. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387084zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387084423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387084.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles